    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIn a markdown file, `[s` moves *up to* `inlineMisspelledCode`, whereas `]s` can skip it.\n\nThis bisects to dcbe5bdd96749a47098904224ceb09bfafd87ae7 (#37907).\n`:lua vim.treesitter.stop()` fixes the issue.\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nSave the following as `a.md`:\n```markdown\nline1\nline2\n`line3`\nline4\nline5\n```\n\n`nvim --clean -c 'set spell' a.md`\n\n- `]s` works as expected: line1 → line2 → line4 → line5 → (search hit BOTTOM, continuing at TOP) line1 → …\n- `[s` does not: line1 → (search hit TOP, continuing at BOTTOM) line5 → line4 → (search hit TOP, continuing at BOTTOM) line5 → line4 → …\n\nMore specifically, it seems to happen when the first bad word on a line is inside `code`.\n\n```markdown\n`[s` and `]s` work as expected.\n\nline1\nline2 `line3`\nline4\nline5\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`[s` goes backward to misspelled words beyond inline code: line5 → line4 → line2 → line1 → line5 → …\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.13.0-dev-337+g0039a13fe4\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.2.388\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty 1.3.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
